In 1971 the Parish decided to establish a new ministry that would aid working parents and children, Kindergarten and a Day Care Center.  The first director of the Day Care Center was Sr. Mary Mercy an Ursuline Sister.  The Day Care was located in the west wing of the school building.  In 1989, the Kindergarten Program was taken over by the Owensboro Catholic Consolidated School System. 

When Sr. Mary Mercy retired in 1978,  Ms. Juanita Fogle became Director and served in that capacity until June, 2003.  Micki Brantley Howard is the current director of the day care center.  The Day Care Center has recently expanded its services to include infants and toddlers.  The Day Care Center has an outstanding reputation as a Christian based, quality child care center that strives to meet the needs of parents and children.   Referrals for Day Care Services can be made by contacting the Day Care at 684-7456.  Days and hours of operation are Monday - Friday,  6:30 A.M. - 5:30 P.M.

Day Care Advisory Council:   The Day Care Advisory Council was formed in 2003.  Additional volunteers with an interest in this ministry are needed.   Nine individuals will serve as the Advisory Council with each serving a three year term.  Advisory Council members are appointed by the Pastor.

column11:
At Southern Oaks Elementary our mission is to celebrate the Success Of Every Student.  As the principal of SOES, it is my responsibility to ensure that we are indeed doing just that!  I believe we must celebrate and cultivate the whole child.  Therefore, our emphasis at SOES is to build knowledge through many avenues.  Each child has a strength that we need to find and capitalize on so that each and every child feels successful at school.

To do this, we need to not only focus on our teaching, but on our student’s learning as well.  We will implement the use of specific learning targets in our classroom and the use of specific feedback on student work.  We will celebrate small successes each day through Stallion Salutes.  We will offer a club day each month to give students the opportunities to explore and find new areas of interest and strengths. In addition to Club Day, we will offer after school clubs such as Art Club, Archery Club, Running Club and Lego Club. 

Our staff believes in our mission and pledges to give 100% each day to celebrate the Success Of Every Student!

The Head Start Program of Audubon Area Community Services will continue to operate in sixteen Western Kentucky counties at 59 sites.  These sites are located in the following counties: Caldwell, Christian, Crittenden, Daviess,

Hancock,Henderson, Hopkins, Livingston, Lyon, McLean, Muhlenberg, Ohio, Todd, Trigg, Union, and Webster.  Our current grantee funded enrollment is 1702 Head Start (including 41 Head Start enrollments through delegate agreement with Western Kentucky University Child Care Consortium); 156 Early Head Start; and 40 Migrant Head Start (in partnership with Community Action Council for Lexington Fayette).

Audubon is blended with the state preschool program, known as KERA preschool because it was established under the Kentucky Education Reform Act (KERA) in 1990.  Audubon operates collaborative blended Head Start/Preschool classrooms in all counties except Henderson and Todd.  The current KERA preschool enrollment is 1,297 children.

Early in 1921, Ben H. Cook, superintendent of Christian County schools, held a meeting in the Sinking Fork area to discuss the possibility of consolidating three schools. In the fall of that same year an attractive four room building had been constructed and two buses had been purchased to transport students.

Sinking Fork school held its first high school graduation in 1926. In 1939 a gymnasium was built and in 1941 a modern brick building was constructed around the gymnasium. In 1951 a new wing of classrooms was added and another wing in 1954. In 1959 students in the 10th, 11th and 12th grades were moved to the high school on Glass Avenue in Hopkinsville. Head Start has had a strong impact on communities and early childhood programs across the country and is one of the longest-running programs to address systemic poverty in the United States.

In 1964, the Federal Government asked a panel of child development experts to draw up a program to help communities meet the needs of disadvantaged preschool children. The panel report became the blueprint for Project Head Start.

Project Head Start, launched as an eight-week summer program by the Office of Economic Opportunity in 1965, was designed to help break the cycle of poverty by providing preschool children of low-income families with a comprehensive program to meet their emotional, social, health, nutritional and psychological needs. Recruiting children age three to school age entry, Head Start was enthusiastically received by educators, child development specialists, community leaders, and parents across the Nation.

In 1969, Head Start was transferred from the Office of Economic Opportunity to the Office of Child Development in the U.S. Department of Health, Education and Welfare, and has now become a program within the Administration for Children and Families in the Department of Health and Human Services.

Head Start has evolved into a program that provides education, health and social services. Education includes preschool education to national standards that have become de facto standards for all U.S. preschools. Health services include screenings, health check–ups, and dental check–ups. Social services provide family advocates to work with parents and assist them in accessing community resources.

KRFDC’s Head Start program began in 1966. The earliest records indicate that in 1974 Head Start was funded at $435,424 and served 330 children (95 in Clark, 60 in Estill, 115 in Madison, and 60 in Powell County. At the time, the program employed 73 people.

Since 1966, KRFDC Head Start services have expanded into Garrard, Jackson, Laurel, and Rockcastle counties. In 2009 KRFDC Early Head Start was funded to serve children in Clark, Estill, Madison, and Powell counties.

Today, KRFDC’s Head Start funding is $6.7 million to provide Head Starts services to 856 children ages 3-4 in Clark (210), Estill (53), Garrard (46), Jackson (102), Laurel (117), Madison (175), Powell (128), and Rockcastle (25) counties; as well as Early Head Start services to 84 children birth-3 years-old in Clark (10), Estill (8), Madison (38), and Powell (28) counties. Currently, the program employs 115 people.

Established in 1965, Head Start promotes school readiness for children, ages three to five, in low-income families by offering educational, nutritional, health, social and other services. Head Start programs promote school readiness by enhancing the social and cognitive development of children through the provision of educational, health, nutritional, social and other services to enrolled children and families. Programs actively engage parents in their children's learning and help them in making progress toward their educational, literacy and employment goals. Significant emphasis is placed on the involvement of parents in the administration of local Head Start programs.

column11: We are a licensed child care provider capable of caring for a maximum of 33 children ages 6 weeks -12 years of age. School age children are 85$/week for summer care and 5$/day for before/after school care. We participate in the STARS for kids program and are currently at Level 1. All staff are trained in childcare and we have plenty of experience dealing with children. We want to give your child a loving nurturing enviroment. When your child is of age, usually around 2, they will begin basic skills to help them in their education. Our goal is to have them Kindergarten ready by ages 4-5. They will be taught fundamentals such as color, shapes, numbers( rote counting and recognition) letters and sounds, basic math and how to become self sufficient and independant. We will help children with their social, mental and physical skills. All staff employees are required to have a negative TB skin test on file along with a Background check and a Child Abuse & Neglect Check. All staff must complete 15 hours of Child Development training per year. We are always in compliance with state regulations and never over the staff/child ratios. Infants - 1 Year is 5:1, 1-2 year old is 6:1, 2-3 year olds is 10:1 and 3-5 year olds is 12:1. We also participate in the federal food program and serve the children a nutritious breakfast, lunch and snack. We hold 1 annual parent, child and staff assembly or get together. We feel that all involved are part of The Learning Ladder family! We look forward to providing the best childcare possible to your child and are here to answer any questions and concerns you may have.

Audubon Area Community Services Head Start program has a 16 county service delivery area, serving over 3,000 children from low-income families and children with disabilities through five programs  administered by this department.

The Head Start program's primary mission is to provide comprehensive early childhood services for eligible children. All children are provided a safe, nurturing environment in which they are given the opportunity to learn and experience success, with additional services provided to children with special needs.  The program ensures that the children are provided with medical and dental examinations and nutritious meals.  Head Start offers a variety of program options from part-day classrooms to full-day, full year classrooms.  Specific programs include Migrant Head Start which focuses on the area's migrant population and Early Head Start which offers a home-based option for very young children.

The agency's Head Start program is one of only twenty-five programs in the nation to have achieved recognition as a national Program of Excellence by the National Head Start Association.  The program has maintained this distinction since 2000.

column11:
Trinity’s academic program is superior, designed to transcend a mere transfer of information to teach the art and love of learning. We are distinctively classical in approach, meaning we see learning as integrated, hands-on, and oriented towards developing students’ abilities to think critically, communicate persuasively, and live virtuously.

More importantly, however, Trinity’s entire culture is thoroughly integrated around a Christian worldview. Many Christian schools claim this as a core value, but a scan of our curriculum and a visit to our community will reveal the significance this carries in our approach. The Christian worldview teaches all truth is God’s truth; skillfulness is worthless without moral grounding (the ability to know and live a good life); and every student has been given both a particular calling and set of gifts from God to utilize for the common good and for His glory. This shapes the unique nature of our educational community, which is to help students discover more and more of God, His world, themselves, and their part in His Grand Story.

Our North Lexington Family YMCA is located at the head of the Legacy Trail, providing an array of indoor and outdoor amenities perfect for active adults and families. The North Lexington Y boasts a thriving youth sports program, as well swim lessons, exercise classes, a full gym, and more.

Our nursery holds up to ten infants. Our crib beds meet the new state requirements and are equipped with angel care monitors which have a sensor that is placed under the mattress to help prevent SIDS.

Our daycare is laid out in a classroom floorplan we have a one year old classroom and a two year old classroom. Our three year olds, four year olds, and after school children will alternate between the language arts learning center, the science/math/dramatic play learning center and the indoor play room. The one and two year olds will also be allotted time in the indoor play room as well. Our outdoor play area is fenced completely and has yet to be completed due to the cold weather. We plan to have it completed in late spring.

Children will have plenty of play time but will also learn with us. We will work on reading, writing, science, math, and social skills on an age/level appropriate basis. We will also assist in potty training.

We have a camera system which allows our parents to log in and view the daycare online. This allows for an ease of mind during the day. This also allows us to ensure that our children are being provided the best care possible and that our employees meet our expectations for learning and safety. Our camera system will be turned off during nap time for the children's privacy.

column11:
Welcome to Jody Richards Elementary School!  It is going to be an exciting year ahead. We look forward to working together to ensure our students are college, career, and citizenship ready for their futures.

The finishing touches are being put on our beautiful new building. Our gym is already decked out in red, white, and blue. We are named for the Honorable Representative Jody Richards, so we have chosen these patriotic colors as our new school colors. The students have voted for the Rockets as this new mascot!  

We plan to communicate, connect, and celebrate with students and families during this transition time. We will be using this website and emails as our way of communicating unless we know a family needs a hard copy mailed to them. Please visit this site often as we will be adding many updates.


To start making connections and celebrate our new building, we are planning many family events to help us join together as a new school community.  Part of this goal is for the students to become very comfortable with the physical space before the school year actually begins in August.  Therefore, several exciting evenings are being planned for the next few months. The first was a special Scavenger Hunt of Jody Richards Elementary on March 13th which was a huge success!   We will have other events throughout the summer.

The future of Jody Richards Elementary School is wide open!  We know the students will continue to grow and achieve as we work to maintain the high standard of excellence already established at both Rich Pond and Natcher.  We look forward to this exciting adventure of becoming the new Jody Richards’ school community. We welcome your participation as we prepare our future leaders.
